Very good observation Babs. Let me say that you have many friends and associates here just for the simple fact that you have an interest in ITC, are a researcher and a complex thinker. I think we have shown in the past that we can have a disagreement and still remain friends. You make a lot of good points in your post and I would like to know who removes time from their recordings. I have never removed time from my recordings and see no reason why anyone else would without saying so in an accompanied post.

I have limited experience with the 12-469&#39;s as a single piece of equipment. I have arranged mine per Mike&#39;s, &quot;Spiricomp&quot; design. I have 3, 12-469&#39;s feeding a four channel mixer, which goes into a laptop running DC6 with Soundsoap 2. Mine scan equally spaced on the FM band. I have had pretty good results until recently.

At first the messages were pretty clear but I had a feeling I was getting a different group than I normally have for the last few years. When I would ask about my friends on the other side they would tell me they will look for them. Well about 2 weeks ago the 12-469 arrangement started generating a lot of interference and feedback. I started hearing radio static voices as I use to get with shortwave. Not voice fragments but voices made of static (metallic and robotic). They were breaking through the sweeping. I had a feeling someone else was trying to force their way through. Finally the interference got so bad I was forced to revert back to a simpler method I used before, which is using fan noise. One of the first messages to come across was from a familiar voice telling me and I quote, &quot;your method sucks&quot;. I have not used the 12-469&#39;s since because of the clear messages I have been getting using water and fan noise. That does not mean I have given up
 on the 12-469&#39;s but I won&#39;t use them again until I am persuaded to by my friends on the otherside that they are willing to use and adapt to it. To my knowledge only Misty, Laura and myself use water for recording.

Regards,

Frank R.


